{"title_page": "Traian Vuia, Timi\u0219", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Traian Vuia\n|leader_name=  Vasile Petruescu\n|leader_party= ALDE\n|image_map              = Traian Vuia jud Timis.png\n|area_total_km2          = 69.76\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|48|N|22|4|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Traian Vuia''' (until 1950, ''Bujoru''; {{lang-hu|Bozsor}}) is a commune in [[Timi\u0219 County]], western [[Romania]]. It is composed of six villages: Jupani (''Zsupp\u00e1ny''), S\u0103ceni (''Kissz\u00e9cs\u00e9ny''), Sudria\u0219 (the commune center; ''B\u00e9gaszederjes''), Surducu Mic (''Kisszurdok''), Susani (''B\u00e9gaszusz\u00e1ny'') and Traian Vuia.\n\nIt was the birthplace of inventor and aviator [[Traian Vuia]] (1872\u20131950). It was renamed to commemorate him after his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1172836}}\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Traian Vuia, Timis}}\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{timis-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Traian Vuia\n|leader_name=  Vasile Petruescu\n|leader_party= [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|ALDE]]\n|image_map=\n|area_total_km2          = 69.76\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|48|N|22|4|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Traian Vuia''' (until 1950, ''Bujoru''; {{lang-hu|Bozsor}}) is a commune in [[Timi\u0219 County]], western [[Romania]]. It is composed of six villages: Jupani (''Zsupp\u00e1ny''), S\u0103ceni (''Kissz\u00e9cs\u00e9ny''), Sudria\u0219 (the commune center; ''B\u00e9gaszederjes''), Surducu Mic (''Kisszurdok''), Susani (''B\u00e9gaszusz\u00e1ny'') and Traian Vuia.\n\nIt was the birthplace of inventor and aviator [[Traian Vuia]] (1872\u20131950). It was renamed to commemorate him after his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1172836}}\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Traian Vuia, Timis}}\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{timis-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traian_Vuia,_Timi%C8%99"}
{"title_page": "Vodafone Malta", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Vodafone Malta Limited\n| former_name = Telecell\n| logo = [[File:Vodafone 2017 logo.svg|172px]]\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| parent = [[Monaco Telecom]]\n| caption = \n| foundation = 1989 (as Telecell)\n| location = [[Luqa]], [[Malta]]\n| key_people = CEO, Tamas Banyai\n| industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n| products = [[Mobile phones]] and ancillary products\n| num_employees = 319\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.vodafone.com.mt}}\n}}\n\n'''Vodafone Malta Limited''' (formerly operating as '''Telecell'''), is a [[Malta|Maltese]] [[mobile network operator]] that was previously a subsidiary of the British multinational telecommunications provider [[Vodafone]]. Vodafone Malta is the largest mobile operator in Malta by number of customers.<ref>[https://www.mca.org.mt/articles/key-market-indicators-electronic-communications-and-post-q1-2014-q1-2018 \"MCA Reports\"].</ref> The company offers a full range of Voice, SMS and mobile Data services over 2G, 3G, 4G and 4G+ networks. It was announced on December 19, 2019 that Vodafone Group was to sell their Malta business to Monaco Telecom;<ref name=\"CdM\">{{cite news|language=it|url=https://www.corrieredimalta.com/economia-politica/news/vodafone-cede-la-sua-filiale-maltese-a-monaco-telecom-per-250-milioni-di-euro/|title=Vodafone cede la sua filiale maltese a Monaco Telecom per 250 milioni di euro|work=Corriere di Malta|date=2019-12-23|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"ToM\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/vodafone-malta-on-sale-for-250-million.758248|title=Deal reached to sell Vodafone Malta for \u20ac250 million|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2019-12-19|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> the sale has been completed on 31st of March 2020.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|language=fr, en|url=https://www.monaco-telecom.mc/images/presse/CP_Malte_FR_UK.pdf|format=pdf|title=Monaco Telecom devient le premier op\u00e9rateur mobile \u00e0 Malte \u2013 Monaco Telecom becomes first mobile operator in Malta|date=2020-03-31|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"VF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vodafone.com/news-and-media/vodafone-group-releases/news/vodafone-completes-sale-of-vodafone-malta|title=Vodafone completes sale of Vodafone Malta|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"ToM-2\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/monaco-telecom-completes-250m-buyout-of-vodafone-malta.782477|title=Monaco Telecom completes \u20ac250m buyout of Vodafone Malta|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"TMI\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2020-04-01/business-news/Monaco-Telecom-completes-Vodafone-Malta-acquisition-6736221518|title=Monaco Telecom completes Vodafone Malta acquisition|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nVodafone Malta was set up in 1989 and initially traded under the name Telecell Limited. The very first [[mobile phone|mobile]] call was made on the [[Vodafone]] Malta network in 1990 whilst the first GSM call was made in 1997. Vodafone Malta's international gateway was launched in 2004 making it the first company in Malta to offer resilience and backup on international connectivity to the local business community. The international gateway spans approximately 250&nbsp;km between Malta and Catania carrying three main types of traffic: [[Internet]], [[Voice]] and [[Data]]. During August 2006, Vodafone was the first mobile network operator to deploy 3G followed by the launch of HSDPA for high speed data transmission in December 2006. In June 2007, Vodafone Malta launched fixed broadband based on WiMax technologies.\n\nIn 2008, Vodafone opened its Mobile Network to Virtual Network Operators. This was made possible through an agreement with [[ASPIDER|ASPIDER Solutions]]. One of the virtual operators using the Vodafone network is [[Redtouch Fone]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darmanin|first1=David|title=Mobile wars unlikely to be sweet deal for parties|url=http://archive.maltatoday.com.mt/2010/01/03/t9.html|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=MaltaToday|date=3 January 2010}}</ref> In 2010, Vodafone added another first when it announced the launch of an even faster mobile data service with nationwide download speeds of 14.4Mbit/s. In 2012, another first for Malta was launched by Vodafone. The new 21.6Mbit/s HSPA capability was launched live across all of Vodafone's coverage area. Vodafone started also rolling out the very latest 42Mbit/s capability across key areas and high traffic sites on its network.<ref>Vodafone unveils highest mobile internet speeds : http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20120412/business-news/Vodafone-unveils-highest-mobile-internet-speeds.415155</ref>\n{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} Vodafone Malta announced its roll out of a 4G network in October 2013.<ref>Vodafone brings first 4G network to Malta : http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20131010/local/Vodafone-brings-first-4G-network-to-Malta.489665</ref> It is the first mobile operator in Malta with an operating 4G network and in June 2017 Vodafone Malta has announced 4G+.\n\nIn 2017, Vodafone became the first network to introduce superfast 4.5G to the Maltese islands, making it the country\u2019s fastest network. The new technology allows for the downloading of data at unprecedented speeds \u2013 33 per cent faster than any other network available in Malta and Gozo \u2013 at 300Mbps.\n\nIn October 2018, Vodafone Malta introduced NB-IoT (narrow band IoT) to Malta bringing the next generation IoT technology to the local market.<ref> Vodafone pushes boundaries of connectivity by bringing next generation IoT technology to Malta : http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-10-10/company-news/Vodafone-pushes-boundaries-of-connectivity-by-bringing-next-generation-IoT-technology-to-Malta-6736197568</ref>\n\nOn 19th December 2019, Vodafone Group Plc announced that it has entered into an agreement to sell 100% of Vodafone Malta to Monaco Telecom SAM for a cash consideration equivalent to an Enterprise Value of \u20ac250 million;<ref name=\"ToM\" /><ref name=\"CdM\" /> the sale was accomplished on 31st March 2020.<ref name=\"MT\" /><ref name=\"VF\" /><ref name=\"ToM-2\" /><ref name=\"TMI\" />\n\n==Head Office==\nVodafone Malta's head office is located in SkyParks Business Centre, at the [[Malta International Airport]]. Vodafone also operates a number of retail outlets across the Maltese Islands offering a range of customer services. On 11 November 2014, Vodafone opened its first destination store in Malta. The store occupies 417 sq metres and is situated on the Birkirkara Bypass.<ref>New Store : http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2014-11-11/company-news/Vodafone-Malta-opens-new-destination-store-6736125487</ref>\n\n== Vodafone Malta Foundation ==\nThe ''Vodafone Malta Foundation'' was set up in 2003 and is an entirely separate entity from Vodafone Malta's commercial organisation. The Foundation focuses on supporting projects that make a difference to the Maltese Community. Its prime objective is to partner up with NGOs and co-create, support and fund projects that fall under the Connecting for Good Programme. The aim of this programme is to harness the power of innovative mobile technology to bring about social change. The Chairperson of the Foundation was Gemma Mifsud Bonnici until 2015. The current Chairman is Michel Macelli.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Maltese mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Malta]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Luqa]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Malta]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Vodafone Malta Limited\n| former_name = Telecell\n| logo = [[File:Vodafone 2017 logo.svg|172px]]\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| parent = [[Monaco Telecom]]\n| caption = \n| foundation = 1989 (as Telecell)\n| location = [[Luqa]], [[Malta]]\n| key_people = CEO, Tamas Banyai\n| industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n| products = [[Mobile phones]] and ancillary products\n| num_employees = 319\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.vodafone.com.mt}}\n}}\n\n'''Vodafone Malta Limited''' (formerly operating as '''Telecell'''), is a [[Malta|Maltese]] [[mobile network operator]] and a subsidiary of the British multinational telecommunications provider [[Vodafone]]. Vodafone Malta is the largest mobile operator in Malta by number of customers.<ref>[https://www.mca.org.mt/articles/key-market-indicators-electronic-communications-and-post-q1-2014-q1-2018 \"MCA Reports\"].</ref> The company offers a full range of Voice, SMS and mobile Data services over 2G, 3G, 4G and 4G+ networks. It was announced on December 19, 2019 that Vodafone Group was to sell their Malta business to Monaco Telecom;<ref name=\"CdM\">{{cite news|language=it|url=https://www.corrieredimalta.com/economia-politica/news/vodafone-cede-la-sua-filiale-maltese-a-monaco-telecom-per-250-milioni-di-euro/|title=Vodafone cede la sua filiale maltese a Monaco Telecom per 250 milioni di euro|work=Corriere di Malta|date=2019-12-23|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"ToM\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/vodafone-malta-on-sale-for-250-million.758248|title=Deal reached to sell Vodafone Malta for \u20ac250 million|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2019-12-19|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> the sale has been completed on 31st of March 2020.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|language=fr, en|url=https://www.monaco-telecom.mc/images/presse/CP_Malte_FR_UK.pdf|format=pdf|title=Monaco Telecom devient le premier op\u00e9rateur mobile \u00e0 Malte \u2013 Monaco Telecom becomes first mobile operator in Malta|date=2020-03-31|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"VF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vodafone.com/news-and-media/vodafone-group-releases/news/vodafone-completes-sale-of-vodafone-malta|title=Vodafone completes sale of Vodafone Malta|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"ToM-2\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/monaco-telecom-completes-250m-buyout-of-vodafone-malta.782477|title=Monaco Telecom completes \u20ac250m buyout of Vodafone Malta|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"TMI\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2020-04-01/business-news/Monaco-Telecom-completes-Vodafone-Malta-acquisition-6736221518|title=Monaco Telecom completes Vodafone Malta acquisition|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nVodafone Malta was set up in 1989 and initially traded under the name Telecell Limited. The very first [[mobile phone|mobile]] call was made on the [[Vodafone]] Malta network in 1990 whilst the first GSM call was made in 1997. Vodafone Malta's international gateway was launched in 2004 making it the first company in Malta to offer resilience and backup on international connectivity to the local business community. The international gateway spans approximately 250&nbsp;km between Malta and Catania carrying three main types of traffic: [[Internet]], [[Voice]] and [[Data]]. During August 2006, Vodafone was the first mobile network operator to deploy 3G followed by the launch of HSDPA for high speed data transmission in December 2006. In June 2007, Vodafone Malta launched fixed broadband based on WiMax technologies.\n\nIn 2008, Vodafone opened its Mobile Network to Virtual Network Operators. This was made possible through an agreement with [[ASPIDER|ASPIDER Solutions]]. One of the virtual operators using the Vodafone network is [[Redtouch Fone]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darmanin|first1=David|title=Mobile wars unlikely to be sweet deal for parties|url=http://archive.maltatoday.com.mt/2010/01/03/t9.html|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=MaltaToday|date=3 January 2010}}</ref> In 2010, Vodafone added another first when it announced the launch of an even faster mobile data service with nationwide download speeds of 14.4Mbit/s. In 2012, another first for Malta was launched by Vodafone. The new 21.6Mbit/s HSPA capability was launched live across all of Vodafone's coverage area. Vodafone started also rolling out the very latest 42Mbit/s capability across key areas and high traffic sites on its network.<ref>Vodafone unveils highest mobile internet speeds : http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20120412/business-news/Vodafone-unveils-highest-mobile-internet-speeds.415155</ref>\n{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} Vodafone Malta announced its roll out of a 4G network in October 2013.<ref>Vodafone brings first 4G network to Malta : http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20131010/local/Vodafone-brings-first-4G-network-to-Malta.489665</ref> It is the first mobile operator in Malta with an operating 4G network and in June 2017 Vodafone Malta has announced 4G+.\n\nIn 2017, Vodafone became the first network to introduce superfast 4.5G to the Maltese islands, making it the country\u2019s fastest network. The new technology allows for the downloading of data at unprecedented speeds \u2013 33 per cent faster than any other network available in Malta and Gozo \u2013 at 300Mbps.\n\nIn October 2018, Vodafone Malta introduced NB-IoT (narrow band IoT) to Malta bringing the next generation IoT technology to the local market.<ref> Vodafone pushes boundaries of connectivity by bringing next generation IoT technology to Malta : http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-10-10/company-news/Vodafone-pushes-boundaries-of-connectivity-by-bringing-next-generation-IoT-technology-to-Malta-6736197568</ref>\n\nOn 19th December 2019, Vodafone Group Plc announced that it has entered into an agreement to sell 100% of Vodafone Malta to Monaco Telecom SAM for a cash consideration equivalent to an Enterprise Value of \u20ac250 million;<ref name=\"ToM\" /><ref name=\"CdM\" /> the sale was accomplished on 31st March 2020.<ref name=\"MT\" /><ref name=\"VF\" /><ref name=\"ToM-2\" /><ref name=\"TMI\" />\n\n==Head Office==\nVodafone Malta's head office is located in SkyParks Business Centre, at the [[Malta International Airport]]. Vodafone also operates a number of retail outlets across the Maltese Islands offering a range of customer services. On 11 November 2014, Vodafone opened its first destination store in Malta. The store occupies 417 sq metres and is situated on the Birkirkara Bypass.<ref>New Store : http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2014-11-11/company-news/Vodafone-Malta-opens-new-destination-store-6736125487</ref>\n\n== Vodafone Malta Foundation ==\nThe ''Vodafone Malta Foundation'' was set up in 2003 and is an entirely separate entity from Vodafone Malta's commercial organisation. The Foundation focuses on supporting projects that make a difference to the Maltese Community. Its prime objective is to partner up with NGOs and co-create, support and fund projects that fall under the Connecting for Good Programme. The aim of this programme is to harness the power of innovative mobile technology to bring about social change. The Chairperson of the Foundation was Gemma Mifsud Bonnici until 2015. The current Chairman is Michel Macelli.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Maltese mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Malta]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Luqa]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Malta]]\n", "name_user": "Symbol", "label": "safe", "comment": "owner change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vodafone_Malta"}
{"title_page": "Altana", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{primary sources|date=August 2019}}\n{{Advert|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n | name = ALTANA AG\n | logo = Logo-altana-2-.gif\n | type = [[Joint-stock company]]\n | founder = [[Herbert Quandt]]\n | area_served =\n | key_people =\n*  Martin Babilas, CEO<ref name=\"altana.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/management/martin-babilas.html|title=Martin Babilas - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com|access-date=6 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001102543/https://www.altana.com/company/management/martin-babilas.html|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*  Dr. Klaus-J\u00fcrgen Schmieder, Chair, Supervisory Board<ref name=\"Supervisory Board\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/supervisory-board.html|title=Supervisory Board - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com|access-date=27 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308040404/https://www.altana.com/company/supervisory-board.html|archive-date=8 March 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Susanne Klatten]] - sole owner and deputy chairman<ref>{{cite web\n|title= Forbes\n|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/susanne-klatten/#471e430436b4\n|accessdate= 8 November 2019\n}}</ref>\n | industry = [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]]\n | genre =\n | products =\n | services =\n | revenue = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 2.225 billion (2019)<ref name=\"CR2019\">[https://www.altana.com/fileadmin/altana/press-news/corporate-report-2019/altana_corporate_report_2019.pdf \"Altana Corporate Report 2019\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230194902/http://www.altana.com/press-news/press-news.html?no_cache=1&newsID=4081 |date=30 December 2017 }}, ''altana.com''. Retrieved 31 December 2019.</ref>\n | operating_income =\n | net_income =\n | assets =\n | equity =\n | owner =\n | num_employees = 6,476 (2018)<ref name=\"CR2019\" />\n | parent =\n | divisions = [[BYK Additives & Instruments]], [[ECKART Effect Pigments]], [[Elantas]], Savage Laboratories,\n [[Actega]].\n | subsid =\n | footnotes =\n | intl =\n| foundation = 1977\n | location_city = [[Wesel]]\n | location_country = [[Germany]]\n | location =\n | locations =\n | market cap =\n | homepage = [http://www.altana.com/ www.altana.com]\n }}\n'''Altana AG''' (styled as '''ALTANA''') is a [[Germany|German]] chemical company headquartered in [[Wesel]]. It was created in 1977 through the spin-off of divisions of the Varta Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/history.html|title=History - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com}}</ref> The first CEO was [[Herbert Quandt]].\n\nThe group comprises the divisions [[BYK Additives & Instruments|BYK]] (coating additives and instruments), Eckart (metal effect pigments and metallic printing inks), Elantas (insulation materials for the electrical and electronics industries) and Actega (coatings and sealant compounds for the packaging industry).\n\nThe Altana Group has 47 production facilities and 65 service and research laboratories worldwide. In 2019, the company, with about 6,500 employees, posted revenues of approximately \u20ac2.25 billion.<ref name=\"CR2019\" />\n\n== History ==\nAltana's roots go back to 1873, when Heinrich Byk founded the chemicals factory Dr. Heinrich Byk Chemische Fabrik in [[Oranienburg]].  The company grew, and in 1931 it was renamed BYK-Gulden Lomberg. In 1941 majority control of the company was acquired by AFA (Akkumulatoren-Fabrik AG) which was renamed [[VARTA]] in 1962.  In 1977 VARTA was split into three companies, one of which was Altana.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.altana.com/company/history.html|publisher=Altana AG|accessdate=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1977 to 2010, Altana was publicly traded on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]]. Altana was also admitted to trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] from 2002 to 2007.\n\nOn 19 December 2006 the majority of [[shareholder]]s voted to approve the sale of the pharmaceuticals division to the Danish company [[Nycomed]]. Nycomed is owned by an investment consortium led by [[Nordic Capital]] and [[Credit Suisse]]. With the sale of the pharmaceuticals division, headquartered in [[Konstanz]], [[Germany]], Altana lost a major pillar of its business. At that time, 9,000 of the company's 13,500 employees were working for Altana in the pharmaceuticals sector, generating two-thirds of the company's total revenue. And indeed, the balance-sheet revenues fell by around 60 percent in 2006, but gained over six percent in 2007.\n\nThe patent for pantaprazole, the main revenue-generator for the former pharmaceuticals division, expired in 2009/2010. While the Altana Management Board justified the divestiture of the pharmaceutical business with delays in the approval of new products, increased research and development costs as well as strict regulatory requirements in the [[US]] and [[Europe]], shareholder activists asserted that the Management Board had invested too little in the pharmaceutical business in the preceding years and had failed to develop successor products in time to compensate for the revenue losses to be expected due to the expiry of the pantaprazole patent at the end of the decade.\n\nThe pharmaceuticals division was sold for \u20ac4.6 billion. The entire proceeds from the sale were disbursed to the shareholders, who received a special dividend of \u20ac33 per share. Critics expressed discontent that the main shareholder benefited most from the sale of the pharmaceuticals division.\n\nUntil 1 January 2007, the company was organized into the pharmaceuticals division Altana Pharma AG, formerly Byk Gulden Lomberg Chemische Fabrik, headquartered in Konstanz, and the specialty chemicals division Altana Chemie AG based in [[Wesel]]. Since the sale of the pharmaceutical business to Nycomed, Altana has been operating exclusively in the specialty chemicals segment. This restructuring was accompanied by a change in the company logo, which was unified across all subsidiaries.\n\nOn 6 November 2008, main shareholder [[SKion GmbH]] (Germany, owned by [[Susanne Klatten]]) issued a public takeover offer of \u20ac13 per share for all outstanding shares, an action which drove up the stock price. A company spokesperson stated that the intention was to delist the company from public trading. To achieve this, SKion issued a second takeover offer of \u20ac14 per share to the remaining shareholders on 9 November 2009.\n\nOn 30 December 2008, the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] announced that Altana would be removed from its [[MDAX]] index, as the increase in the share held by SKion had pushed the portion of stock held in free float to under ten percent. By June 2010, SKion held 95.04 percent of all shares.\n\nIn Germany, the stock was traded mainly on the Frankfurt and Stuttgart Exchanges and the [[Xetra (trading system)|Xetra]] platform; internationally, it was admitted to trading on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and the [[NASD Group]], now FINRA, in the US.\n\nAfter SKion acquired the entire Altana stock through a squeeze-out, trading in this stock was suspended effective 27 August 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.altana.de/ Website of Altana AG]\n* [http://www.altana.com/press-news/dates-events/report-on-the-business-year-2013.html Report on the Business Year 2013], Altana AG\n\n[[Category:Chemical companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Companies based in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Chemical companies established in 1977]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in West Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{primary sources|date=August 2019}}\n{{Advert|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n | name = ALTANA AG\n | logo = Logo-altana-2-.gif\n | type = [[Joint-stock company]]\n | founder = [[Herbert Quandt]]\n | area_served =\n | key_people =\n*  Martin Babilas, CEO<ref name=\"altana.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/management/martin-babilas.html|title=Martin Babilas - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com|access-date=6 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001102543/https://www.altana.com/company/management/martin-babilas.html|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*  Dr. Klaus-J\u00fcrgen Schmieder, Chair, Supervisory Board<ref name=\"Supervisory Board\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/supervisory-board.html|title=Supervisory Board - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com|access-date=27 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308040404/https://www.altana.com/company/supervisory-board.html|archive-date=8 March 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Susanne Klatten]] - sole owner and deputy chairman<ref>{{cite web\n|title= Forbes\n|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/susanne-klatten/#471e430436b4\n|accessdate= 8 November 2019\n}}</ref>\n | industry = [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]]\n | genre =\n | products =\n | services =\n | revenue = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 2.307 billion (2018)<ref>[http://www.altana.com/press-news/press-news.html?no_cache=1&newsID=4081 \"Half-Year Results: ALTANA Achieves Operating Sales Increase\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230194902/http://www.altana.com/press-news/press-news.html?no_cache=1&newsID=4081 |date=30 December 2017 }}, ''altana.com''. Retrieved 31 December 2018.</ref>\n | operating_income =\n | net_income =\n | assets =\n | equity =\n | owner =\n | num_employees = 6,428 (2018)<ref>[http://www.altana.com/company/success-story/employees.html \"Success due to our employees\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001095504/https://www.altana.com/company/success-story/employees.html |date=1 October 2018 }}, ''altana.com''. Retrieved 31 December 2018.</ref>\n | parent =\n | divisions = [[BYK Additives & Instruments]], [[ECKART Effect Pigments]], [[Elantas]], Savage Laboratories,\n [[Actega]].\n | subsid =\n | footnotes =\n | intl =\n| foundation = 1977\n | location_city = [[Wesel]]\n | location_country = [[Germany]]\n | location =\n | locations =\n | market cap =\n | homepage = [http://www.altana.com/ www.altana.com]\n }}\n'''Altana AG''' (styled as '''ALTANA''') is a [[Germany|German]] chemical company headquartered in [[Wesel]]. It was created in 1977 through the spin-off of divisions of the Varta Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/company/history.html|title=History - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com}}</ref> The first CEO was [[Herbert Quandt]].\n\nThe group comprises the divisions [[BYK Additives & Instruments|BYK]] (coating additives and instruments), Eckart (metal effect pigments and metallic printing inks), Elantas (insulation materials for the electrical and electronics industries) and Actega (coatings and sealant compounds for the packaging industry).\n\nThe Altana Group has 52 production facilities and 60 service and research laboratories worldwide. In 2018, the company, with about 6,400 employees, posted revenues of approximately \u20ac2.3 billion.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altana.com/press-news/press-news.html?no_cache=1&newsID=4956|title=About ALTANA - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.com}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAltana's roots go back to 1873, when Heinrich Byk founded the chemicals factory Dr. Heinrich Byk Chemische Fabrik in [[Oranienburg]].  The company grew, and in 1931 it was renamed BYK-Gulden Lomberg. In 1941 majority control of the company was acquired by AFA (Akkumulatoren-Fabrik AG) which was renamed [[VARTA]] in 1962.  In 1977 VARTA was split into three companies, one of which was Altana.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.altana.com/company/history.html|publisher=Altana AG|accessdate=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1977 to 2010, Altana was publicly traded on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]]. Altana was also admitted to trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] from 2002 to 2007.\n\nOn 19 December 2006 the majority of [[shareholder]]s voted to approve the sale of the pharmaceuticals division to the Danish company [[Nycomed]]. Nycomed is owned by an investment consortium led by [[Nordic Capital]] and [[Credit Suisse]]. With the sale of the pharmaceuticals division, headquartered in [[Konstanz]], [[Germany]], Altana lost a major pillar of its business. At that time, 9,000 of the company's 13,500 employees were working for Altana in the pharmaceuticals sector, generating two-thirds of the company's total revenue. And indeed, the balance-sheet revenues fell by around 60 percent in 2006, but gained over six percent in 2007.\n\nThe patent for pantaprazole, the main revenue-generator for the former pharmaceuticals division, expired in 2009/2010. While the Altana Management Board justified the divestiture of the pharmaceutical business with delays in the approval of new products, increased research and development costs as well as strict regulatory requirements in the [[US]] and [[Europe]], shareholder activists asserted that the Management Board had invested too little in the pharmaceutical business in the preceding years and had failed to develop successor products in time to compensate for the revenue losses to be expected due to the expiry of the pantaprazole patent at the end of the decade.\n\nThe pharmaceuticals division was sold for \u20ac4.6 billion. The entire proceeds from the sale were disbursed to the shareholders, who received a special dividend of \u20ac33 per share. Critics expressed discontent that the main shareholder benefited most from the sale of the pharmaceuticals division.\n\nUntil 1 January 2007, the company was organized into the pharmaceuticals division Altana Pharma AG, formerly Byk Gulden Lomberg Chemische Fabrik, headquartered in Konstanz, and the specialty chemicals division Altana Chemie AG based in [[Wesel]]. Since the sale of the pharmaceutical business to Nycomed, Altana has been operating exclusively in the specialty chemicals segment. This restructuring was accompanied by a change in the company logo, which was unified across all subsidiaries.\n\nOn 6 November 2008, main shareholder [[SKion GmbH]] (Germany, owned by [[Susanne Klatten]]) issued a public takeover offer of \u20ac13 per share for all outstanding shares, an action which drove up the stock price. A company spokesperson stated that the intention was to delist the company from public trading. To achieve this, SKion issued a second takeover offer of \u20ac14 per share to the remaining shareholders on 9 November 2009.\n\nOn 30 December 2008, the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] announced that Altana would be removed from its [[MDAX]] index, as the increase in the share held by SKion had pushed the portion of stock held in free float to under ten percent. By June 2010, SKion held 95.04 percent of all shares.\n\nIn Germany, the stock was traded mainly on the Frankfurt and Stuttgart Exchanges and the [[Xetra (trading system)|Xetra]] platform; internationally, it was admitted to trading on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and the [[NASD Group]], now FINRA, in the US.\n\nAfter SKion acquired the entire Altana stock through a squeeze-out, trading in this stock was suspended effective 27 August 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.altana.de/ Website of Altana AG]\n* [http://www.altana.com/press-news/dates-events/report-on-the-business-year-2013.html Report on the Business Year 2013], Altana AG\n\n[[Category:Chemical companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Companies based in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Chemical companies established in 1977]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in West Germany]]\n"