ivisions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kashgar"}
{"title_page": "Tormac", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Tormac\n|other_name=V\u00e9gv\u00e1r\n|leader_name= Csaki Karol \n|leader_party= UDMR\n|image_map              = Tormac jud Timis.png\n|area_total_km2          = 134.08\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|31|N|21|30|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Tormac''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]].\n\n==Names==\nNames in other languages: {{lang-de|Rittberg}}; {{lang-hu|V\u00e9gv\u00e1r}}.\n\n==Villages==\nIt is composed of three villages: Cad\u0103r (''K\u00e1d\u00e1r''), [[\u0218ipet, Timi\u0219|\u0218ipet]] (''Sebed'') and Tormac.\n\n==Demographics==\n===Ethnic groups===\nAt the 2011 census, 60.1% of inhabitants were [[Romanians]], 37.5% [[Hungarians]] and 1.6% other.\n\n===Religion===\nAt the 2002 census, 51% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 37.6% [[Reformed Church of Romania|Reformed]], 6.6% [[Roman Catholic]] and 2.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]].\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{Timi\u0219-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Tormac\n|other_name=V\u00e9gv\u00e1r\n|leader_name= Csaki Karol \n|leader_party= [[Democratic Alliance of Hungarians in Romania|UDMR]]\n|image_map=\n|area_total_km2          = 134.08\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|31|N|21|30|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Tormac''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]].\n\n==Names==\nNames in other languages: {{lang-de|Rittberg}}; {{lang-hu|V\u00e9gv\u00e1r}}.\n\n==Villages==\nIt is composed of three villages: Cad\u0103r (''K\u00e1d\u00e1r''), [[\u0218ipet, Timi\u0219|\u0218ipet]] (''Sebed'') and Tormac.\n\n==Demographics==\n===Ethnic groups===\nAt the 2011 census, 60.1% of inhabitants were [[Romanians]], 37.5% [[Hungarians]] and 1.6% other.\n\n===Religion===\nAt the 2002 census, 51% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 37.6% [[Reformed Church of Romania|Reformed]], 6.6% [[Roman Catholic]] and 2.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]].\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{Timi\u0219-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tormac"}
{"title_page": "Mary Elizabeth Barnicle", "text_new": "{{infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n'''Mary Elizabeth (Barnicle) Cadle''' (April 17, 1891 - November 26, 1978) was a [[Folklore studies|folklorist]], Medieval English literature professor, and activist interested in women's and African-American rights, suffrage, and the labor movement.  She collected and made numerous field recordings of folk songs and stories throughout the South and [[Caribbean]] between from the mid 1930s until the early 1950s.  She collected with [[Alan Lomax]] and later her husband, [[Tillman Cadle]].\n\n== Early life ==\n'''Mary Elizabeth Barnicle''' was born on April 17, 1891 in [[Natick, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5279|title=Collection: Papers of Mary Elizabeth Barnicle Cadle, 1915-1978 {{!}} HOLLIS for Archival Discovery|website=hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>  Her family later moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island]], where they remained throughout her education and where she taught evening school from 1910\u20131911. Barnicle attended [[Brown University]], where she participated in the [[Women's suffrage|suffrage movement]] and graduated with her bachelor's degree in 1913.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJZGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=mary+elizabeth+barnicle+education&source=bl&ots=-weSPEGMPF&sig=ACfU3U3QQ9NdwQ0Rk-owkE6dh50IRWk4cw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwji4sfqk6znAhXHZd8KHT3SDoI4ChDoATAEegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=mary%20elizabeth%20barnicle%20education&f=false|title=Bryn Mawr College Calendar: Graduate Courses|last=College|first=Bryn Mawr|date=1915|publisher=The College|language=en}}</ref>  She was a graduate scholar in English at [[Bryn Mawr College]] from 1913-1914 and while continuing to teach, completed her Ph.D. around 1920. Cadle taught English and Folklore at the [[University of Minnesota]] and [[Connecticut College]]. She spent a year teaching at [[Antioch College]] and left in 1924 to join the faculty of the [[New York University]] - where she remained throughout the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/397482781/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=31 Aug 1924, 22 - Dayton Daily News at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBarnicle's home in [[Greenwich Village]] was considered part of the folk music revival of the 1930s and 1940s.  [[Lead Belly|Leadbelly]], [[Aunt Molly Jackson]], and [[Sarah Ogan Gunning|Sarah Ogan]],  among others, would spend time in her home.<ref name=\":0\" /> By the mid 1930s, Barnicle and [[Zora Neale Hurston]] had struck up a friendship, with Hurston speaking in Barnicle's NYU classes and Barnicle joining Hurston in [[Harlem]] to meet and record her friends.  Previously, Barnicle had also become friends with [[John Lomax|John]] and [[Alan Lomax]] and proposed a collection trip with Alan during his summer break from college. However, in May 1935, she proposed instead that she, Hurston, and Alan Lomax would tour and collect throughout the Southeast.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sV48asr7T4MC&pg=PT87&lpg=PT87&dq=alan+lomax+walnut+darkening&source=bl&ots=NzSwnVhvY3&sig=ACfU3U3-xQVswApYAQyjrOGXXVKlWKEntA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv58OzvK7nAhVZmHIEHQbNDf8Q6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=barnicle&f=false|title=Alan Lomax: The Man Who Recorded the World|last=Szwed|first=John|date=2010-12-30|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-19034-0|language=en}}</ref> That summer, while he was on summer break from the [[University of Texas at Austin|University of Texas]], Lomax. Hurston, and Barnicle toured the Southern United States and parts of the [[The Bahamas|Bahamas]] (specifically [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] and [[Andros, Bahamas|Andros]]) to record folk songs and stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/197688445/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=31 Aug 1935, Page 6 - The Burlington Free Press at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>  Hurston ended up only accompanying them for part of the trip due to disagreements with Barnicle; Hurston returned home and Barnicle and Lomax continued to the Bahamas without her. During their trip, Alan was in charge and had two years of collecting and recording experience, Barnicle kept notes and had knowledge of ballads and folk songs, and Hurston served as their gatekeeper and guide to Southern and African American culture.<ref name=\":3\" />  Together, they attended gatherings, meetings, and met with individuals with a large recording device, on which they made over two hundred records of African American folk songs and stories.\n\nDuring that same year, Tillman Cadle, a labor activist and coal miner, would travel to New York to have surgery on a shoulder injury and while there, he met Barnicle through his friend, [[Jim Garland]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1745|title=Cadle, Tillman,, 1902-1994 {{!}} ArchivesSpace Public Interface|website=archives.etsu.edu|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>  Cadle and Barnicle shared a love and interest in documenting and collecting ballads.  Around 1936, Cadle and Barnicle married but they lived apart until after World War II. During that time, Cadle would frequently travel between New York City and Kentucky, making extended visits to both locations and he and Barnicle would make field recordings of folk artists.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1746|title=Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth, 1891-1978 {{!}} ArchivesSpace Public Interface|website=archives.etsu.edu|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> Cadle would also often serve as gatekeeper for Barnicle to record in Appalachia as he would contact and set up meetings with individuals for her to record.<ref name=\":4\" />  Between 1937 and 1949 Mary Elizabeth and Tillman Cadle traveled around eastern Tennessee and Kentucky recording folk songs, love songs, ballads, and work songs.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMary Elizabeth Barnicle recorded interviews for the [[Library of Congress]]' \"[https://www.loc.gov/collections/voices-remembering-slavery/about-this-collection Voices Remembering Slavery: Freed People Tell Their Stories]\" (formerly \"Voices From the Days of Slavery: Former Slaves Tell Their Stories\") collection.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/235809830/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=26 Feb 2004, Page 5-7 - Chicago Tribune at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She also recorded and worked with Lead Belly (Huddie Ledbetter), she took him around New York City and introduced him to others in the folk music movement, namely [[Woody Guthrie]] and [[Pete Seeger]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/409803930/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=8 May 2005, 42 - Daily News at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She joined the faculty of the [[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee - Knoxville]] as an English instructor in October, 1946 but retired 3 years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/594255785/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=12 Oct 1946, 11 - The Knoxville News-Sentinel at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 1949, Tillman Cadle moved to Rich Mountain Gap, near [[Townsend, Tennessee]], not far from [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville,]] and Barnicle joined him there.<ref name=\":1\" />  Barnicle retired in 1950, and she and Cadle moved to Natick, Massachusetts, they would live there and in Worcester until 1971, when they moved back to their home in Rich Mountain Gap.\n\n== Legacy ==\nBarnicle was a member of the [[Modern Language Association]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TklEKOjs7ZoC&pg=PA123&lpg=PA123&dq=mary+elizabeth+barnicle+education&source=bl&ots=6-IbQl7CLR&sig=ACfU3U0OK5fCNA8Q4lc2_-vX6wxQtaszxg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwji4sfqk6znAhXHZd8KHT3SDoI4ChDoATAFegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=mary%20elizabeth%20barnicle%20education&f=false|title=Politics of Education: Essays from Radical Teacher|last=O'Malley|first=Susan Gushee|last2=Rosen|first2=Robert C.|date=1990-01-01|publisher=SUNY Press|year=|isbn=978-0-7914-0355-6|location=|pages=124|language=en}}</ref> and Vice President of the Folklore Society of Tennessee in 1949.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/605029334/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=29 Oct 1949, 7 - Chattanooga Daily Times at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She passed away November 26, 1978 at her and Cadle's Rich Mountain Gap Home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w60k6x04|title=Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth, 1891-1978 - Social Networks and Archival Context|website=snaccooperative.org|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nMary Elizabeth Barnicle collections are held at:\n\n* ''[https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1746 Mary Elizabeth Barnicle and Tillman Cadle Collection]'', Archives of Appalachia, East Tennessee State University - Collection contains biographical information, audio tapes and discs, field recordings, and an interview with Tillman Cadle.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* ''[https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5279 Papers of Mary Elizabeth Barnicle Cadle, 1915-1978],'' Schlesing Library, Radcliffe Institute, Harvard University - Collection contains lecture notes, tales and songs, correspondence, and photographs<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Recordings from Mary Elizabeth Barnicle and Alan Lomax's trip throughout the American South and Bahamas are held in the American Folklife Collection of the Library of Congress.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:Suffragists]]\n[[Category:Folklorists]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n'''Mary Elizabeth (Barnicle) Cadle''' (April 17, 1891 - November 26, 1978) was a [[Folklore studies|folklorist]], Medieval English literature professor, and activist interested in women's and African-American rights, suffrage, and the labor movement.  She collected and made numerous field recordings of folk songs and stories throughout the South and [[Caribbean]] between from the mid 1930s until the early 1950s.  She collected with [[Alan Lomax]] and later her husband, [[Tillman Cadle]].\n\n== Early life ==\n'''Mary Elizabeth Barnicle''' was born on April 17, 1891 in [[Natick, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5279|title=Collection: Papers of Mary Elizabeth Barnicle Cadle, 1915-1978 {{!}} HOLLIS for Archival Discovery|website=hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>  Her family later moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island]], where they remained throughout her education and where she taught evening school from 1910-1911. Barnicle attended [[Brown University]], where she participated in the [[Women's suffrage|suffrage movement]] and graduated with her bachelor's degree in 1913.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJZGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=mary+elizabeth+barnicle+education&source=bl&ots=-weSPEGMPF&sig=ACfU3U3QQ9NdwQ0Rk-owkE6dh50IRWk4cw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwji4sfqk6znAhXHZd8KHT3SDoI4ChDoATAEegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=mary%20elizabeth%20barnicle%20education&f=false|title=Bryn Mawr College Calendar: Graduate Courses|last=College|first=Bryn Mawr|date=1915|publisher=The College|language=en}}</ref>  She was a graduate scholar in English at [[Bryn Mawr College]] from 1913-1914 and while continuing to teach, completed her Ph.D. around 1920. Cadle taught English and Folklore at the [[University of Minnesota]] and [[Connecticut College]]. She spent a year teaching at [[Antioch College]] and left in 1924 to join the faculty of the [[New York University]] - where she remained throughout the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/397482781/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=31 Aug 1924, 22 - Dayton Daily News at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBarnicle's home in [[Greenwich Village]] was considered part of the folk music revival of the 1930s and 1940s.  [[Lead Belly|Leadbelly]], [[Aunt Molly Jackson]], and [[Sarah Ogan Gunning|Sarah Ogan]],  among others, would spend time in her home.<ref name=\":0\" /> By the mid 1930s, Barnicle and [[Zora Neale Hurston]] had struck up a friendship, with Hurston speaking in Barnicle's NYU classes and Barnicle joining Hurston in [[Harlem]] to meet and record her friends.  Previously, Barnicle had also become friends with [[John Lomax|John]] and [[Alan Lomax]] and proposed a collection trip with Alan during his summer break from college. However, in May of 1935, she proposed instead that she, Hurston, and Alan Lomax would tour and collect throughout the Southeast.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sV48asr7T4MC&pg=PT87&lpg=PT87&dq=alan+lomax+walnut+darkening&source=bl&ots=NzSwnVhvY3&sig=ACfU3U3-xQVswApYAQyjrOGXXVKlWKEntA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv58OzvK7nAhVZmHIEHQbNDf8Q6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=barnicle&f=false|title=Alan Lomax: The Man Who Recorded the World|last=Szwed|first=John|date=2010-12-30|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-19034-0|language=en}}</ref> That summer, while he was on summer break from the [[University of Texas at Austin|University of Texas]], Lomax. Hurston, and Barnicle toured the Southern United States and parts of the [[The Bahamas|Bahamas]] (specifically [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] and [[Andros, Bahamas|Andros]]) to record folk songs and stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/197688445/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=31 Aug 1935, Page 6 - The Burlington Free Press at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>  Hurston ended up only accompanying them for part of the trip due to disagreements with Barnicle; Hurston returned home and Barnicle and Lomax continued to the Bahamas without her. During their trip, Alan was in charge and had two years of collecting and recording experience, Barnicle kept notes and had knowledge of ballads and folk songs, and Hurston served as their gatekeeper and guide to Southern and African American culture.<ref name=\":3\" />  Together, they attended gatherings, meetings, and met with individuals with a large recording device, on which they made over two hundred records of African American folk songs and stories.\n\nDuring that same year, Tillman Cadle, a labor activist and coal minor, would travel to New York to have surgery on a shoulder injury and while there, he met Barnicle through his friend, [[Jim Garland]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1745|title=Cadle, Tillman,, 1902-1994 {{!}} ArchivesSpace Public Interface|website=archives.etsu.edu|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>  Cadle and Barnicle shared a love and interest in documenting and collecting ballads.  Around 1936, Cadle and Barnicle married but they lived apart until after World War II. During that time, Cadle would frequently travel between New York City and Kentucky, making extended visits to both locations and he and Barnicle would make field recordings of folk artists.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1746|title=Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth, 1891-1978 {{!}} ArchivesSpace Public Interface|website=archives.etsu.edu|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> Cadle would also often serve as gatekeeper for Barnicle to record in Appalachia as he would contact and set up meetings with individuals for her to record.<ref name=\":4\" />  Between 1937 and 1949 Mary Elizabeth and Tillman Cadle traveled around eastern Tennessee and Kentucky recording folk songs, love songs, ballads, and work songs.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMary Elizabeth Barnicle recorded interviews for the [[Library of Congress]]' \"[https://www.loc.gov/collections/voices-remembering-slavery/about-this-collection Voices Remembering Slavery: Freed People Tell Their Stories]\" (formerly \"Voices From the Days of Slavery: Former Slaves Tell Their Stories\") collection.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/235809830/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=26 Feb 2004, Page 5-7 - Chicago Tribune at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She also recorded and worked with Lead Belly (Huddie Ledbetter), she took him around New York City and introduced him to others in the folk music movement, namely [[Woody Guthrie]] and [[Pete Seeger]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/409803930/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=8 May 2005, 42 - Daily News at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She joined the faculty of the [[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee - Knoxville]] as an English instructor in October, 1946 but retired 3 years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/594255785/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=12 Oct 1946, 11 - The Knoxville News-Sentinel at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 1949, Tillman Cadle moved to Rich Mountain Gap, near [[Townsend, Tennessee]], not far from [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville,]] and Barnicle joined him there.<ref name=\":1\" />  Barnicle retired in 1950, and she and Cadle moved to Natick, Massachusetts, they would live there and in Worcester until 1971, when they moved back to their home in Rich Mountain Gap.\n\n== Legacy ==\nBarnicle was a member of the [[Modern Language Association]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TklEKOjs7ZoC&pg=PA123&lpg=PA123&dq=mary+elizabeth+barnicle+education&source=bl&ots=6-IbQl7CLR&sig=ACfU3U0OK5fCNA8Q4lc2_-vX6wxQtaszxg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwji4sfqk6znAhXHZd8KHT3SDoI4ChDoATAFegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=mary%20elizabeth%20barnicle%20education&f=false|title=Politics of Education: Essays from Radical Teacher|last=O'Malley|first=Susan Gushee|last2=Rosen|first2=Robert C.|date=1990-01-01|publisher=SUNY Press|year=|isbn=978-0-7914-0355-6|location=|pages=124|language=en}}</ref> and Vice President of the Folklore Society of Tennessee in 1949.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/605029334/?terms=Mary+Elizabeth+Barnicle|title=29 Oct 1949, 7 - Chattanooga Daily Times at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> She passed away November 26, 1978 at her and Cadle's Rich Mountain Gap Home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w60k6x04|title=Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth, 1891-1978 - Social Networks and Archival Context|website=snaccooperative.org|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nMary Elizabeth Barnicle collections are held at:\n\n* ''[https://archives.etsu.edu/agents/people/1746 Mary Elizabeth Barnicle and Tillman Cadle Collection]'', Archives of Appalachia, East Tennessee State University - Collection contains biographical information, audio tapes and discs, field recordings, and an interview with Tillman Cadle.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* ''[https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5279 Papers of Mary Elizabeth Barnicle Cadle, 1915-1978],'' Schlesing Library, Radcliffe Institute, Harvard University - Collection contains lecture notes, tales and songs, correspondence, and photographs<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Recordings from Mary Elizabeth Barnicle and Alan Lomax's trip throughout the American South and Bahamas are held in the American Folklife Collection of the Library of Congress.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnicle, Mary Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:Suffragists]]\n[[Category:Folklorists]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: minor \u2192 miner,typo(s) fixed: May of 1935 \u2192 May 1935, 1910-1911 \u2192 1910\u20131911", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Elizabeth_Barnicle"}
